# Emily Test Rules (pytest)

## Framework & Config
- pytest + pytest-asyncio (auto mode — no need for `@pytest.mark.asyncio` on every test)
- pytest-cov for coverage reporting
- respx for mocking HTTP calls (not `unittest.mock` for HTTP)
- time-machine for time-dependent tests (not `freezegun`, not `time.sleep()`)
- hypothesis for property-based tests where applicable

## Structure
- Tests live under `tests/unit/` mirroring the source directory structure
- Benchmarks live under `tests/benchmarks/`
- `conftest.py` for shared fixtures — never import fixtures between test files directly
- Group tests in classes only when they share meaningful setup; prefer module-level functions

## Naming
- Test functions: `test_<what>_<condition>_<expected_outcome>`
- Example: `test_create_episode_duplicate_id_raises_conflict`
- Fixture names should be nouns describing what they provide, not verbs

## Writing Tests
- Prefer `pytest.mark.parametrize` over copy-paste variations
- Mock at the boundary (LLM fleet, Qdrant, ZeroMQ, filesystem) — don't mock internal helpers
- Every test must have a single, clear assertion focus
- Test async code with `async def test_*` — pytest-asyncio auto mode handles the rest
- Use `respx` for mocking HTTP calls to external APIs and LLM endpoints

## Fixtures
- Use the narrowest scope: `function` > `module` > `session`
- Provide `EmilySettings` fixtures with test-appropriate defaults
- Memory fixtures should use in-memory backends, not SQLite files
- Mark slow/integration tests with `@pytest.mark.integration`

## What Not To Do
- Never use `time.sleep()` — use `time-machine` to control time
- Never assert on internal function call counts unless testing a contract
- Never leave `print()` or `breakpoint()` in committed tests
- Never test third-party library behavior (e.g., that ZeroMQ delivers messages)
